case_name: Co-operative Credit Society v. Raja Nandlal

facts.text: This appeal arises out of execution proceedings of a decree passed by an arbitrator under the Co-operative Credit Societies Act.

anchor.surface_text: This appeal arises out of execution proceedings of a decree passed by an arbitrator under the Co-operative Credit Societies Act.

facts.text: The appeal was presented to the Judicial Committee of the State and is number before us under article 374 4  of the Constitution.

facts.text: Raja Nandlal was a member of the decree-holder Society and was also its debtor.

anchor.surface_text: The first point for consideration in this appeal is as regards the jurisdiction of the Registrar functioning under the Co-operative Credit Societies Act in respect to execution of decrees. The decision of this question depends on the interpretation to be placed on the language employed in section 42, clause d , of the Co-operative Credit Societies Act, 1340 F., as amended.

arguments.claim: Civil Procedure Code analogy inapplicable; Registrar unlike court passing decree which retains execution jurisdiction even after transfer

anchor.surface_text: under the Civil Procedure Code. Under the Code a civil court passing a decree is also the court executing the decree. It has a dual capacity, 1 of the court passing the decree, and 2 of the executing court. The Registrar, it appears, has the first capacity of a civil court but he has not been placed in the matter of execution in the same capacity as a civil court passing a decree.

holdings.text: The analogy of decisions given in respect of civil courts is not available in interpreting this Act. Under the Civil Procedure Code the parent court, i.e., the court passing the decree, always retains jurisdiction to execute the decree even if it has been transferred to one or more courts for the purpose of execution.

anchor.surface_text: under the Civil Procedure Code. Under the Code a civil court passing a decree is also the court executing the decree....Under the Civil Procedure Code the parent court, i.e., the court passing the decree, always retains jurisdiction to execute the decree even if it has been transferred to one or more courts for the purpose of execution. The position however in the case of the Registrar is entirely different.

holdings.reasoning_summary: CPC parent court retains execution jurisdiction despite transfers; Registrar has no such jurisdiction, only certification power.
